Energy densities are $u_E=\frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_0 E^2$
$$
u_B=\frac{1}{2} \frac{B^2}{\mu_0}
$$
So, energy required to setup a uniform electric field in cube of side $10 \mathrm{~cm}$ is
$$
\begin{aligned}
U_E & =u_E \times \text { Volume of cube }=\frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_0 E^2 \times l^3 \\
& =\frac{1}{2} \times 8.9 \times 10^{-12} \times\left(10^7\right)^2 \times(0.1)^3 \\
& =4.45 \times 10^{-12+14-3} \\
& =4.45 \times 10^{-1}=0.445 \mathrm{~J}
\end{aligned}
$$
and energy required to setup a uniform magnetic field in cube of side $10 \mathrm{~cm}$ is
$$
\begin{aligned}
U_B & =u_B \times \text { Volume of cube } \\
& =\frac{B^2 l^3}{2 \mu_0}=\frac{0.25 \times 0.25 \times(0.1)^3}{4 \pi \times 10^{-7} \times 2}=25 \mathrm{~J}
\end{aligned}
$$

The given,
$L_1=108 \mathrm{mH}, N_1=600$ turns, $N_2=500$ turns and $L_2=$ ?
By self-inductance of a plane coil
$$
\begin{aligned}
&amp; L_1=\frac{\mu_0 \pi N_1^2 a_1}{2} \\
&amp; L_2=\frac{\mu_0 \pi N_2^2 a_2}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$
From the Eqs. (i) and (ii), we get
$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{L_1}{L_2} &amp; =\left(\frac{N_1}{N_2}\right)^2 \quad\left(\because a_1=a_2\right) \\
\frac{108}{L_2} &amp; =\left(\frac{600}{500}\right)^2 \\
L_2 &amp; =\frac{108 \times 25}{36} \\
L_2 &amp; =3 \times 25=75 \mathrm{mH}
\end{aligned}
$$
